            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Kim\u2019s story is one of quiet rebellion and an unwavering commitment to craft. The only son of Korean immigrants who ran a bustling dry-cleaning business in the Outer Richmond, David grew up surrounded by the scent of steam and the rhythm of hard work. His parents envisioned a future for him in medicine or engineering, a stable path paved with predictable success. But David was captivated by a different kind of order: the intricate ballet of a well-run hotel, the seamless service of a fine dining restaurant.\n\nIgnoring his parents' gentle disappointment, he pursued a Bachelor's in Hospitality Management. His career began in the trenches of luxury hotels, climbing from a front desk agent at the Fairmont to a Food & Beverage Director at a boutique SoMa property. The long hours and dedication to perfection took a toll on his personal life, contributing to a divorce in his early forties. The split was amicable but left him with a sense of solitary purpose, pouring all his energy into his profession.\n\nHis turning point came eight years ago when he was headhunted for the General Manager position at \"The Aerie,\" an exclusive private members club discreetly tucked away in a Nob Hill high-rise. Here, his talent for orchestrating flawless experiences found its ultimate expression. He became the master of a world built on discretion, managing the whims of tech moguls and old San Francisco money with an unflappable calm.\n\nNow 51, David's life is a study in curated routine. He lives in a modern Hayes Valley condo, its minimalist decor a stark contrast to the club's opulent traditionalism. His 3.8-mile commute on the MUNI is his time to decompress, observing the city he\u2019s called home his entire life. He\u2019s seen Hayes Valley transform from a gritty bypass to a chic hub, a change he views with pragmatic acceptance.\n\nWhile he has achieved professional success, David dreams of a quieter third act. He fantasizes about owning a small, perfect wine bar in a neighborhood like Glen Park\u2014a place of his own creation, free from boards and demanding members. More than that, he hopes to build a lasting partnership, having learned that true hospitality begins with making space for another person in your own life."
