            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers his tenth birthday, a rare treat at the Fairmont. Stepping into the grand lobby, the scent of lilies replaced the familiar steam of his parents\u2019 dry-cleaners. It wasn\u2019t the luxury that captivated him, but the perfect, quiet order\u2014the doorman\u2019s nod, the seamless check-in, a world orchestrated for comfort. In that hushed grandeur, he saw his future not in chemicals and hangers, but in the art of the perfect welcome. It was the first time his parents\u2019 dream felt smaller than his own.\n\n2.\nHe was 18, sitting at the small kitchen table in their Outer Richmond apartment. When he said the words \u201cHospitality Management,\u201d the silence that followed was heavier than any argument. His father simply nodded, a deep line etched between his brows, while his mother turned back to the stove. It wasn't anger, but a profound, weary sadness. In their quiet disappointment, David found a stubborn resolve. He would have to prove that his definition of a good life was worth the heartbreak he was causing them.\n\n3.\nIt was close to midnight in his early forties. He came home from the hotel to find his wife, Sarah, sitting in the dark, a suitcase by the door. \"You are an impeccable host, David,\" she said, her voice hollowed out. \"You just don't live here anymore.\" The simple, devastating truth landed. He had spent years orchestrating perfect moments for everyone but her. That night, his single-minded dedication to his craft revealed its true price, leaving him with a mastery of service and a profoundly empty home.\n\n4.\nEight years ago, during his first week as General Manager at The Aerie, he stood alone by the floor-to-ceiling windows after the last member departed. The city was a glittering tapestry below. He had reached the pinnacle his younger self had dreamed of\u2014absolute master of a flawless world. A deep, quiet pride filled him, but it was followed by an acute awareness of the silence. In that opulent room, he realized his professional triumph was also the precise measure of his solitude.\n\n5.\nOn his MUNI ride home last winter, the train stalled in Glen Park. Through the rain-streaked window, he saw a tiny, bustling bistro, laughter fogging the glass as the owner poured wine for a couple. It wasn't the curated perfection of The Aerie; it was something warmer, more genuine. A space built for connection, not discretion. In that brief, stalled moment, David saw his third act\u2014not in a Nob Hill high-rise, but behind a small bar of his own, finally creating a welcome for himself."
